# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# HTTP headers for lavern.ai (Netlify-style _headers file)
#
# Defence in depth, with one calibrated exception: 'unsafe-inline' on
# script-src and style-src. The rationale lives below the policy.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/*
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=(), interest-cohort=()
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://plausible.io; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://fonts.googleapis.com https://api.fontshare.com; font-src 'self' https://fonts.gstatic.com https://cdn.fontshare.com; img-src 'self' data: https://api.dicebear.com; media-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' https://plausible.io https://api.dicebear.com https://api.fontshare.com https://cdn.fontshare.com; frame-ancestors 'none'; base-uri 'self'; form-action 'self'

# CSP — what 'unsafe-inline' is doing here and what mitigates it
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# lavern.ai is a static drag-and-drop deploy: one HTML file, no build
# pipeline, no Netlify Functions, no per-request nonces. To keep the
# zero-RTT first paint that the editorial design depends on, the page
# ships with one inline <style> block (the entire stylesheet), one
# inline <script> block (the page interactions), and one inline JSON-LD
# block for structured data. The embedded /demo/ SPA additionally
# renders React with 48 `style="..."` attributes in the body.
#
# Replacing all of that with externals + per-script hashes is a real
# CSP win, but at the cost of (a) two extra round trips on first
# paint, and (b) recomputing hashes on every CSS/JS tweak. We accepted
# the trade-off for v1 and tightened everything else instead:
#
#   default-src 'self'          — no fallback wildcard
#   frame-ancestors 'none'      — no embedding in any frame anywhere
#   form-action 'self'          — forms can only post back to lavern.ai
#   base-uri 'self'             — <base> can't be hijacked to change
#                                 the document's effective origin
#   img-src 'self' data: dicebear — no third-party image loaders
#   connect-src — only the four hosts we actually talk to
#   no `'unsafe-eval'` anywhere — eval / Function() blocked
#
# What 'unsafe-inline' on script-src does NOT enable:
#   · eval, new Function(), setTimeout(string) — still blocked
#   · loading remote scripts that aren't in the allowlist
#   · any kind of injection via DOM-based sources we don't sanitise
#
# The realistic attack vector it leaves open is: a stored/reflected
# XSS in our own content. The marketing page renders zero user-supplied
# strings, so that vector reduces to "compromise the GitHub repo."
# If an attacker has push access to AnttiHero/lavern, CSP isn't the
# layer holding the line.
#
# Tracked for tightening in https://github.com/AnttiHero/lavern/issues
# (extract inline assets + hash JSON-LD + drop unsafe-inline).

# ── Long-cache the things that have content-hash filenames ──────────
/img/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

/architecture/img/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

/claw/crab.jpg
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

/demo/assets/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# ── Install scripts — plain text so curl | sh / irm | iex work, and
# so the security-minded visitor can fetch and inspect before running.
/install.sh
  Content-Type: text/x-shellscript; charset=utf-8
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=300

/install.ps1
  Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=300
